/i> ‘reed’ + <i>ford</i> (e.g. Rodford and Rudford (Gloucestershire)), and the Oxfordshire placename may derive from Old English <i>rād</i> ‘riding’ + <i>ford</i>, probably meaning ‘ford which can be crossed on horseback’. This English name has been established in Ireland (Wexford) since the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Retford of Worlaby was born about 1354, in Worlaby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Ralph Retford of Castlethorpe. He married Catherine Paynell before May 1385. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1402, at the age of 49, his occupation is listed as speaker of the house of commons. He died before 16 June 1409."},"et":{"about 1354–before 16 June 1409":"umbes 1354–enne 16. juunit 1409","1354–1409":"1354–1409","1350–1397":"1350–1397","1388–1459":"1388–1459","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1 October 1402":"1. oktoober 1402","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1459":"1459","1325":"1325","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1397":"1397","about 1354":"umbes 1354","before 16 June 1409":"enne 16. juunit 1409","after 1374":"pärast 1374","1409":"1409","after 1388":"pärast 1388","before May 1385":"enne maid 1385","Worlaby, Lincolnshire, England":"Worlaby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1354–before 16 June 1409":"noin 1354–ennen vuotta 16. kesäkuuta 1409","1354–1409":"1354–1409","1350–1397":"1350–